{
  "id": "019d38eb-a6fc-7610-84be-68ed443112c2",
  "content": "# Structural Intelligence P3: Barrel File and __init__.py Resolution -- Decision Record (2026-03-29)\n## What: Improved wire_pipeline_relations() target resolution with barrel file and __init__.py fallbacks.\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. HashMap file index: built once per wire_pipeline_relations() call, converts target file lookup from O(n) to O(1). Uses &str keys borrowing from processed slice (zero-copy).\n2. Fallback chain via or_else: direct match -> JS/TS barrel (index.ts/tsx/js/jsx) -> Python __init__.py. Each stage only fires on miss. Existing Rust CRATE_REF resolution unaffected.\n3. Extension probe order: .ts -> .tsx -> .js -> .jsx matching TypeScript's own module resolver priority.\n4. Python init.py: converts dots to slashes (package.submodule -> package/submodule/__init__.py). Runs unconditionally on miss (low cost: one allocation + one HashMap miss for non-Python paths).\n5. Extracted resolve_target() helper for reuse across all three resolution strategies.\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- Source-side from_idx lookup is still O(n) linear scan. A composite key HashMap (source_file, start_line) -> idx would complete the optimization. Follow-up item.\n- Barrel and __init__.py fallbacks fire unconditionally for all languages. Low practical risk since phantom paths must exist in file_index to produce false matches. Could gate on heuristics in future.\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Nothing blocked. The refactoring was clean and all 5 reviewers approved without blocking issues.",
